ennia and recounts the most disastrous flood in the history of California and the West, which occurred in 1861–62. The authors show that, while the West may have temporarily buffered itself from such harsh climatic swings by creating artificial environments and human landscapes, our modern civilization may be ill-prepared for the future climate changes that are predicted to beset the region. They warn that it is time to face the realities of the past and prepare for a future in which fresh water may be less reliable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aClimatic changeszWest (U.S.)xForecasting. 0aClimatic changeszWest (U.S.). 0aHydrologyzWest (U.S.) 0aHydrologyzWest (U.S.). 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh  aartificial environments.  abenign climate.  acalifornia.  aclimate change science.  aclimate change.  aclimate.  aclimatology.  aearth sciences.  aecology.  aengaging.  aenvironment and ecology.  aenvironment.  aenvironmental reads in 2020.  aexperiments.  aextended droughts.  aflood.  afresh water.  ageology.  ahistory of the west.  ahistory.  ahuman landscapes.  anature.  aphenomenon.  aplanetary science.  apopular science.  aretrospective.  ascience biology.  ascientists.  asocial issues.  atumultuous climate.  aunited states.  aus western history.  awater.  aweather.  awestern region.1 aMalamud-Roam, Frances, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026855540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095480940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954809423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954809/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backli